{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> τρίοδος</b> [ῐ], ἡ, <br /> ={τριοδία}, <b>a meeting of three roads,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 911, 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 11.38 \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>] (where the <i>plural</i> [conjecture] is used for the <i>singular</i>,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare 2nd c.BC: Moschus Bucolicus 1.2, “epigram Gr.” 841 (from Thrace), “IG” 3.1418.2); τροχήλατος σχιστῆς κελεύθου τρίοδος 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Fragmenta - American Journal of Philology” 173, compare 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Supplices” 1212, 5th c.BC: Pherecrates Comicus 130.3 (_anapaest meter_, _plural_), 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Fragmenta” 204 (_plural_), 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Gorgias” 524a, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> [Ἑκάτη] ναίουσ᾽ ἱερὰς τ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 535 (_anapaest meter_); ἁ θεὸς ἐν τριόδοισι 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 2.36 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; the τρίοδοι were frequented by fortune-tellers and loungers, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “Characteres” 16.5, 14, 2nd c.AD: Aristides Rhetor “Orationes” 22 (19). 10; φαρμακοπώλης ἐκτριόδου 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 9.823; ἐκτῆς τ. ἰατροί [prev. author] 10.786: hence οἷα ἐκ τριόδου\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>], i. e. vulgar, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Hist.Conscr.” 16, etc.; λοιδορίαι ἐξ ἐργαστηρίων καὶ τριόδων 2nd-3rd c.AD: Dio Cassius Historicus 46.4 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; of certain women, τρίοδοί τινες.. ἐγένοντο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Clearchus Historicus 25 (τριοδίτιδες conjecture Lobeck). \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> proverbial also of persons in doubt, ἐν τριόδῳ δ᾽ ἕστηκα Thgn.[same place]; στὰς.., καθάπερ ἐν τ. γενόμενος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 799c; ἐν τ. εἰμί 2nd c.AD: Zenobius Paroemiographus 3.78, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__4</b></Level3> a measure in Egypt, μέτρῳ τῷ καλουμένῳ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “BGU” 920.21 (2nd c.AD). \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__5</b></Level3> <b>the 'trivium',</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.AD: Simplicius Philosophus “in Aristotelis de Caelo commentaria - Comm. in Arist. Graeca” 131.28. \">Refs 6th c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__6</b></Level3> <i>metaphorically</i>, τὰς συμφωνούσας ἁρμονίας τ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"Ion Eleg. 3.2. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> perhaps ={τετραοδία}, Chrysipp. cited in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Sextus Empiricus Philosophus “Πυρρώνειοι ὑποτυπώσεις” 1.69 (compare “Stoicorum Veterum Fragmenta” 2.206). \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]","strongNumber":"G21246","accentedUnicode":"τρίοδος","shortDef":"the 'trivium'","mediumDef":"the 'trivium'","stepGloss":"the 'trivium'","stepTransliteration":"triodos","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}